articles.author: Andrew Mills, Nidal Al-Mughrabi, James Mackenzie
articles.description: Israel delayed approval of a deal with Palestinian militant group Hamas for a ceasefire in the Gaza Strip and release of hostages, but the United States said it still expected the agreement to go into effect on Sunday as planned.
articles.title: Israel holds off approving Gaza ceasefire but US says deal is on track

articles.author: Joey Roulette
articles.description: A SpaceX Starship prototype failed in space minutes after launching from Texas on Thursday, forcing airline flights over the Gulf of Mexico to alter course to avoid falling debris and setting back Elon Musk's flagship rocket program.
articles.title: SpaceX Starship prototype fails in space after Texas launch

articles.author: Chad Terhune, Rollo Ross
articles.description: Los Angeles officials told most evacuees from the wildfires on Thursday to stay away from their homes at least another week as emergency responders remove toxic waste from incinerated neighborhoods and cut off electricity and gas lines posing a hazard amid the ruins.
articles.title: Los Angeles evacuees told stay away from home at least another week

articles.author: Ju-Min Park, Joyce Lee
articles.description: South Korea's arrested President Yoon Suk Yeol will not attend a new round of questioning by investigators on Friday, his lawyer said, as authorities face an imminent deadline to obtain a warrant to extend his detention or release the embattled leader.
articles.title: South Korea's Yoon refuses questioning again as detention deadline looms

articles.author: Hyunjoo Jin
articles.description: Investigators found bird feathers and blood in both engines of the Jeju Air jet that crashed in South Korea last month, killing 179 people, a person familiar with the probe told Reuters on Friday.
articles.title: Bird feathers, blood found in both engines of crashed jet in South Korea, source says

articles.author: Reuters
articles.description: China's population fell for a third consecutive year in 2024, with the number of deaths outpacing a slight increase in births, and experts cautioning that the downturn will worsen in the coming years.
articles.title: China's population falls for a third consecutive year

articles.author: Makini Brice, Elizabeth Pineau, Dominique Vidalon
articles.description: French Prime Minister Francois Bayrou passed the first test of his new minority government on Thursday as he survived a vote of no-confidence called by the hard left after the centre-left Socialist Party did not back the motion.
articles.title: French PM Bayrou survives no-confidence vote

articles.author: Reuters
articles.description: Taiwan carried out its first execution in five years late on Thursday, upsetting both rights groups and the European Union which called on the government to maintain its de facto moratorium on the death penalty.
articles.title: Taiwan carries out first execution in five years, upsetting EU, rights groups

articles.author: Timour Azhari
articles.description: Iraq is trying to convince powerful armed factions in the country that have fought U.S. forces and fired rockets and drones at Israel to lay down their weapons or join official security forces, Foreign Minister Fuad Hussein said.
articles.title: Iraq wants Iran-backed factions to lay down weapons, foreign minister says

articles.author: David Lewis, Daphne Psaledakis
articles.description: The United States on Thursday imposed sanctions on Sudan's leader, army chief Abdel Fattah al-Burhan, accusing him of choosing war over negotiations to bring an end to the conflict that has killed tens of thousands of people and driven millions from their homes.
articles.title: US issues sanctions on Sudanese army chief Burhan
